<TEXTAREA NAME="ReplyMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[QUOTE]Originally posted by Arhu:
[I]Well, uhh, at last I woke up and now try to clarify my dreams.

As you might have noticed, I really [i]like[/i] tiny little things flying, creeping, lying and hopping around. And it's those little things I especially like in games.
SNES games like "Chrono Trigger", "Zelda" and so on were filled with small creatures, the townsfolk was chatting and everyone went after his very own work, like farming fishing or even putting the children to bed... Everything was moving, was [i]alive[/i]. I didn't like the areas in BG where the trees didn't move at all, although it was rainy or windy.

While RPGs are not only fighting and casting destructive spells at enemies but also walking around, solving puzzles, and just [i]doing[/i] something (eg reading books), my question is:
[b]What other stuff would be nice in a RPG?[/b]

Here are some of my thoughts:
[list]
[*]real readable books; no full 1000 pages tomes, but some short texts would be fine. This was one thing I liked in [i]Ultima ?[/i], for example. Every household had some books lying around that could be read. Sometimes they gave useful information, sometimes they "just" told some history of the world or an adventurer's story. Some famous stories were in every second bookcase, others could be found in the library. And in [i]Unreal[/i] a part of the atmosphere was given through all those notes and messages left behind by unlucky deceased souls.
[*]It would also be fine, if the player could write his own diary. This was a neat feature in DSA; you could write additional notes that were left out by the automatic function. Important things should be marked.
[*]Be able to do other things, eg cook; kindle wood, candles and torches; move or throw  objects around; play the guitar or flute to earn some money in taverns; etc.
[/list] 

There could also be things, persons or events, that have absolutely [i]nothing[/i] to do with the story or so, but are just [i]there[/i]. In all those nice looking action games (ie Unreal and soon Wheel of Time) you have almost no time to marvel at the wondrous world because you have to fight too much. In a RPG you [i]can[/i] (and probably will) admire the small miracles that surround you.

[i]Meow...[/i]
Arhu[/I][/QUOTE]

</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
